Ramen holds the same place for me as Fried Chicken, Loco Moco, and Spam Musubi... Comfort Food. It’s NOT supposed to be gourmet or fine dining... it’s a delicious and flavorful meal that is simple and satisfying. As I have watched some of my “hole-in-the-wall” ramen shops close down and Gourmet Bistro shops open up, I had lost hope that I could find me a good bowl of noodles (& hell no, that packaged stuff we get in the grocery store doesn’t count... well, maybe except for the S&S packs).  So, a long story longer, I visited Menchako when it was in Waikiki back when. When i stopped working in Waikiki, I found Goma-Ichi on Keeaumoku. Then, Goma-Ichi gets crumbled by whatever crazy $10 million dollar condo being built and again I am without a good bowl of noodles. Randomly, looking at this location which, ironically was another noodle shop years ago when I lived i this neighborhood, I see a familiar name.  Came in... saw the owner who I recognized... and was ready for a katsu combo that I knew them for. To my greatest delight, within their current menu, was listed Goma-Ichi TanTan Ramen. Yes, she was friends with the owner and was given the recipe which she now continues to serve in their honor.  Great food. Service with an authentic smile. What you need after a long day at work so you can go home with that warm feeling in your belly.
Excellent varieties of Hakata-style Ramen. No waiting in line for their superb Kurobuta Tonkatsu!!😋🤙

Without a doubt, my goto place for gourmet ramen in Honolulu!  I didn't know how authantic its Hakata Ramen is until I visited the city of Hakata on Kyushu Island, Japan's Southern of the three major island.  It cooks its signature milky color bone broth overnight; rich with flavors yet not at all greasy.  More than just a ramen shop - its Tonkatsu comes with bottomless side salad.  Grind your toasted sesame seeds first and then add dipping sauce for the pork tenderloin to come.  Its Tonkatsu is cheaper yet just as tasty as Ginza Bairin's!  Also on the menu are Nanban Chicken, Gyoza, etc., and cold Asahi beer on tap 😋😋

What a hidden gem in Honolulu (Thanks to Google Map). Delicious Japanese food at very good price. Friendly staff and great service.  Highly recommend this restaurant for others.   We will definitely revisit this place next time we come back.

You can't beat their tonkatsu!  There are three different cuts and I prefer the middle-priced one.  It's nice and soft but not too fatty.  I found the more expensive one too fatty and the less expensive one a little tough.  The waitstaff is always friendly and attentive and the food is always timely and fresh.  It's located on the other side of Keeaumoku from Shingon Mission and Domino's Pizza.  There's plenty of free parking behind the little strip mall it's located in.

If you enjoy using a mortar and pestle as much as I do, then you'll love Menchanko-Tei. Serving traditional cuisine from the Hakata Prefecture of Japan, Menchanko-Tei is authentic and cozy, serving some of the best Japanese dishes in town. The loin katsu and chicken katsu are phenomenally crispy and delicious, served with your own mortar and pestle for grinding the sesame seeds that go with the sauce. The nanban chicken is so flavorful and the menchanko is hearty and tasty. This is a must-try among Honolulu restaurants.
